The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, February 28, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, Feb. 27: The rate of inflation fell marginally by 0.07 per cent to 5.84 per cent for the week ended February 14 due to cheaper vegetables and fruits, eggs and poultry chicken and milk. The point-to-point wholesale price index declined from the previous weeks figure of 5.91 per cent even as prices rose for primary articles and heavy-weighted manufactured products, notably edible oils. The index was 5.34 per cent in the year-ago period.																								 Mumbai, Feb. 27: HSBC is not averse to acquiring stakes in banks, said Niall S. K. Booker, CEO of HSBC India. We always keep an open mind on these things. Our philosophy is never to say never, particularly in markets where we would like to expand, he said.																								 New Delhi, Feb. 27: The government is projecting an India Shining image. However, the country ranks last but one among the 62 most globalised nations as persistent ethnic violence trimmed its trade, investment and overall growth, according to A T Kearneys foreign policy magazine survey.																								 New Delhi, Feb. 27: The governments fiscal deficit rose to Rs 1,00,000 crore till January because of a whopping Rs 36,000 crore surge in expenditure. 																								 Mumbai, Feb. 27: Air-India has identified the US as a major market for growth. It is taking preparatory steps to launch flights to Los Angeles and later to San Francisco, V. Thulasidas, chairman and managing director of Air-India, said today.
